The clay and water representations in a new exhibition.
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" or from the year 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso, which will be exhibited from January 13th in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photo provided by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition in the new premises of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been part of the Studio Arts Program as an artist since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad and Miami. When he was 20 years old, he moved with his family to Southern California.
Siso has shown his excellent ability in numerous series of landscapes, portraits, still lifes in acrylic, pastel, charcoal or watercolor. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs and memories, his colorful compositions demonstrate the full dimension of his interests and his ability in different media. His tropical landscapes and his seascapes show in detailed examples the places of his past. People are also integrated to create important connections between culture, memory and nature. Siso titles his artworks with a mixture of Spanish and English - a sign of the celebrated and important complexities of his life in Los Angeles County. "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" will be inaugurated on Saturday, January 13th with a reception from 6 to 8 pm. The exhibition will be shown until Sunday, March 3rd.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old, integrate the new and thus solve problems
At the district level, we only need to look at Sydney's Central Business District: an originally non-urbanized landscape was first transformed into a settlement with two-story buildings with a maximum height of 46 meters, and then into a market with today's dizzying towers. To a much smaller extent, this can happen in Sydney's market centers around the transport hubs. Even intra-urban districts must continue to develop with a trend towards affordable living space with buildings that will predominantly come from plants in decisive areas. Naturally, this newly formed living space must be convincing in terms of design, and plants, landscape design, and parks must be integrated alongside other essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must also adapt, so that the people responsible in the inner-city district councils, who have a rather critical attitude towards changes, cannot decide alone about the future design of their neighbourhoods. One possibility could be the installation of an independent decision-making body that is committed to high-quality concepts, which are exclusively based on the height of the plants and which take into account space for families, large balconies and community gardens - and visually everything must also be convincing. This could be a task for the current architect of the NSW government, based on a carefully elaborated regulation.
Over the past 10 years, our lives have changed due to technology. Many people work from home and Sydney has gained an impressive network of metros and trams. Shopping online has changed the way we shop, and thanks to smartphones, friends and family can stay in better contact. Exactly such adaptations from one system to another are also possible in our architectural landscape. In this context, the focus of planning should be on adaptive reuse, instead of on a favored preservation of the traditional.
Chris Johnson was NSW Government Architect from 1995 to 2005 and principal director of the NSW planning division from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019, he was also CEO of Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final intervention for women's equality
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this period.
The International Finance Institute is on the verge of introducing a strategy to significantly promote the rights and economic opportunities for girls and women by the year 2030. The plan focuses on optimizing inclusion and resilience by providing access to finance, technical innovations, and changes in public policies and laws.
"The latest research has shown that both social norms and ways of thinking can change and that the integration of men and young people can, for example, achieve that they support gender equality," one can read in a draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results in connection with equality can also be accelerated and scaled up if one understands better... how social norms and mentality influence expectations, priorities, and daily practices."
Changes in thinking are more difficult to quantify than bank loans for women in the countryside or school announcements for girls. Nevertheless, numerous indicators show that the integration of women can move mountains. In Iran, for example, women have become the biggest threat to the Islamic government in 40 years: they have refused to observe laws that force them to cover their heads. In a few of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for female representation in government, for example in India, male resistance to women's right to vote and political activity has diminished.
In some rural communities in Africa, civil society organizations are replacing extremely harmful initiation rites with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, traditional chief of the Maasai Maparasha community, Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and that he would renounce the practice.
The World Bank cites further examples. From 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled and the participation of women in the labor market doubled. The country's gross domestic product more than tripled. The change has developed its own dynamic. The employment of women as paid teachers and health workers in communities has created trust "and the mobility and professional occupation of women have become more acceptable in society."
The bank's plan targets norms and institutions where the generational change has perhaps not yet occurred. In Rwanda, it took more than two decades until the country was able to establish itself as a model for agrarian reforms and promoted the economic empowerment of women. "It serves no one if women are kept down," said Paul Kagame, the president of Rwanda, when he spoke in 2015 for an agrarian reform. "We must change the way of thinking, not just the laws."
The national bank hopes to be able to spread this message.
Germanische Bauern und Lokführer machen deutschen Unternehmern Angst
In Germany, where workers and employers run many businesses together, strikes are largely unheard of. There has practically never been a major wave of strikes. But currently, the "land of co-determination" has to contend with a strike wave, during which not only angry farmers block the roads with their tractors for eight days, but railway employees also strike for three days. Now a doctors' strike is also expected, and doctors' practices were already closed between Christmas and New Year. This "pitchfork mob", as some call it, will put the harmonious labor relations in Germany to the test at the beginning of the year.
The protests were apparently triggered by the government's decision to cut diesel subsidies in agriculture and reduce tax breaks for agricultural vehicles. With these measures, the barrel overflowed for the farmers. They also mobilized other rural workers, who are already suffering under inflation, economic stagnation, and the austerity measures imposed by the government. On January 9, train drivers of passenger and freight trains of the German Railway began a strike to protest against working hours and pay.
To reduce tensions among farmers, the government has declared itself ready to gradually reduce diesel subsidies over the next three years. The vehicle tax exemption will also be maintained. The farmers rejected the concessions, deeming them insufficient. On January 4, Economy Minister Robert Habeck had to leave a ferry after his return from vacation with his family - a group of veiled demonstrators tried to stop him. If the locomotive drivers also remain unimpressed, this could also be bad for the economy, estimates the IW Cologne economic research institute. The railway strike could cost the economy 100 million euros every day if production has to be interrupted. The automotive, chemical and steel industries, the largest economic sectors in Germany, are particularly dependent on rail freight transport.
The atmosphere among the workers is becoming increasingly tense. "Calls for revolution are circulating," Habeck warned. The far-right party Alternative for Germany is doing its best to inflame the protests. In Dresden, the Freien Sachsen, another far-right party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for "extinguishing the torch."
Thomas Puls of the Cologne Institute for Economic Research fears that the protests could damage Germany's image as an economic hub. Local entrepreneurs already fear a German version of the "yellow vest" protests in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and the police intervening with tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, director of the police union, warned in an interview with the Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of a large wave of protests that will reach us this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions to shrink in 2023, and the year ended on a particularly bitter note: an unexpected decline in economic confidence in December. This year could become even more difficult.
Temporary exemptions from the ban on noise for wine producers
In the EU debate on noise avoidance regulations, breweries argue that they are disadvantaged by exceptions for winemakers in recycling targets and deposit refund systems. However, one of the leaders of the European brewing industry association believes that brewers "should mind their own business."
European breweries warn that it would be unfair and perhaps even illegal to accept exceptions regarding reusable packaging as well as deposit-refund systems for wine, but not for beer. Meanwhile, legislators are in the final round of discussions about a new law that should bring about a change in the mountains of packaging in the EU.
The environment ministers concluded a negotiating mandate of the European Council on the proposal for a regulation on packaging and packaging waste before Christmas and thus cleared the way for imminent political discussions with the European Parliament, which have already begun at a professional level.
"Our position is clear," wrote the umbrella federation of European brewers, Brewers of Europe, to the members of the European Parliament and the heads of negotiations of the governments (January 10). "If the targets and prescriptions of the packaging and packaging waste ordinance apply to beer, then there is a legal obligation to apply them to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At their meeting on December 18, the ministers decided on an exception for winegrowers from the obligation to offer 10% of their products in reusable containers in a reuse or refill system until the end of the decade. By 2040, this share should increase to 40%. This exception should also apply to claims that are excluded from systems for deposit refunds. This claim is also supported by the European Parliament and should be introduced within the framework of the proposal by 2029.
The Czech and Belgian ministers expressed their reservations about the unequal treatment of brewers at the meeting on December 18, but they gave their consent. Belgium, which is now in the process of leading the EU presidency and should therefore remain neutral in the negotiations between the governments, hopes that an agreement with the parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, secretary general of the European wine industry association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents around 7,000 winegrowers throughout Europe, does not share the brewers' reservations. He told Euronews that a fair dominated by multinational brewery conglomerates cannot be compared with a sector that consists almost entirely of small national producers.
"According to Sánchez Reacarte, 99% of the domestic wine industry consists of very small to medium-sized businesses. He also questioned the validity of the legal arguments put forward by the breweries. In his opinion, his organization had strived to present "relevant and adequate" information to decision-makers for their own industry."
"It is not my role to evaluate whether the beer industry should have this or that purpose, as that depends on the specific characteristics of its own industry," Sánchez Recarte declared. "Therefore, brewers should mind their own business and concentrate on their own obligations."
Brewers of Europe has started with Euronews a short legal analysis that the association sent last year to the European Commission. In it, it argues that wine and beer are competing products that are "at least partially interchangeable with each other", and that rules that favor one industry over another distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the lobby's chief operating officer, said that brewers already occupy "a leading position" when it comes to sustainable packaging. He drew attention to beer bottles that can be reused around 165 times before they are crushed and recycled after 30 years. They have supported reuse and recycling systems that have already been introduced in many countries.
"That's why we are campaigning for an ambitious regulation concerning packaging and packaging waste. However, we also need equal conditions in packaging legislation, which allow beer and other alcoholic beverages to be treated according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute equally to achieving the goals and supporting the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other approach creates a competitive disadvantage for brewers."
The Biden administration releases economic criminals
Tim Whitehouse, the former lawyer for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and executive director of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, praised the recent improvements by the Biden administration in enforcing environmental law, but also conceded that such efforts face much resistance. "It takes years of reliable funding and political support to develop a good program for enforcing the law," he told me. "Instability in Congress not only demoralizes EPA staff, but also undermines their ability to think strategically long-term."
The EPA's problems are certainly not identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. Its Environment and Natural Resources Division, or ENRD for short, deals with environmental crime. Uhlmann, the Deputy Minister for Law Enforcement, was previously at the EPA, from 1990 to 2007, as head of the environmental crime sector. The EPA sends its most serious civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as a funded authority, is rather poorly based, often relying on others to decide which battles should be fought. In the 2022 fiscal year, the EPA forwarded the fewest cases (88) to the Ministry of Justice since 2000 and concluded the fewest civil proceedings since that date. As mentioned in the environmental integrity project, the EPA concluded an average of 94 civil proceedings and forwarded 106 cases per year to the Minister of Justice even under Trump.
The general procedure of the Ministry of Justice in connection with economic crime cases has been intensively reviewed by the attendees. The observers praised some steps introduced by the Ministry under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice - such as, for example, the creation of a database for economic crime. The Biden Ministry of Justice, however, has also strongly relied on the main witness regulations, which allow companies to delay or avoid criminal prosecution and encourage them to report individual employees to avoid more comprehensive reports. Kenneth Polite Jr., the former Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the Criminal Division, has revised the division's enforcement guidelines for companies to limit prosecutions.
The debate about the shutdown fuels the conflict of the Republicans
In the House of Representatives, conservative opponents of spending today again opposed the party leadership and also cast a series of protest votes. Thus, they protested against the newest spending agreement of Speaker Mike Johnson with the Democrats, which according to them does not foresee sufficient budget reductions.
Even though the Republican from Louisiana is also off topic, the deadline for the deliberation of four of the twelve annual budgets is January 19. Johnson has publicly stated that he will not support a transitional law called "Continuing Resolution" to extend the deadline for those four draft laws to the deadline of the remaining eight on February 2.
In view of the fact that there are only nine more days until the deadline, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate, Mitch McConnell, announced that Congress must deliberate a "Continuing Resolution" to keep the government running. With this, he threatens Johnson with breaking a promise, with which he had initially managed to calm the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver could cause a lively ideological debate about the role of Republicans in questions of expense reduction, which could lead to a partial government shutdown or Johnson's dismissal from office.
The Congressman Matt Rosendale from Montana declared to Newsweek: "I have clearly stated that 'Continuing Resolutions' are not the appropriate way to finance our government, since the budget law of 1974 foresees the approval of 12 credit projects. We have had more than enough time, and if the leaders do not order the committees to do their work and let the members of Congress vote, then that is the reason for the failure."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, in the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington, D.C. Johnson stands before a rebellious Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the level of budget expenditures. Photo: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who is part of the far-right Freedom Caucus group, was one of those who also voted down the midday vote. According to him, the total sum of Johnson's proposal is too small and insufficient to reduce the national debt of 34 trillion dollars.
Rosendale also belongs to the 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law on fiscal responsibility, negotiated between the Democrats and the former speaker Kevin McCarthy, which sets the basic conditions for Johnson's new negotiations with the leader of the Democrats in the Senate, Charles Schumer.
While Johnson praised the merits of his agreement, because it would save about 16 billion dollars in expenses, the Freedom Caucus is of the opinion that he could have achieved even more. Moderate Republicans who supported McCarthy's agreement consider this stance unrealistic and contrary to the Republicans' goal of forcing Congress to approve the twelve drafts individually and not to combine them, as in recent years, with a so-called omnibus procedure in a single vote.
"New year, but the same idiotic behavior from some," Republican Congressman Mike Lawler of New York told Newsweek. "Given that there will be no omnibus procedure, every bill must be debated and voted on separately. It seems that no one will probably need more time for that. And I do not support a shutdown - so I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be brought to an end."
This is the first time since 1996 that Congress has approved all twelve draft laws separately. According to Lawler, it is worth the effort to approve the four draft laws with amendments, to ensure an orderly process. If Congress fails to approve the twelve draft laws by December, the Fiscal Responsibility Act would require a one percent budget reduction in defense and non-defense spending.
Congressman Thomas Massie of Kentucky - probably one of the Republican Party's most fervent opponents of spending - was not one of those who protested against the vote on Wednesday. He did, however, declare that a one-year "Continuing Resolution" with the consequence of a one percent reduction in spending is the most practical way to ensure that the government functions and to simultaneously end the brinkmanship.
The most responsible way to achieve the reduction in expenses, according to Massie, is to approve all twelve draft laws. Many Republicans, however, would not risk a shutdown and thus a one percent reduction in defense spending. The urgency with which the draft laws must be approved could contribute to a sufficient number of Republicans coalescing with the Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and reach an agreement on the funding of government work, even if that would mean that Johnson could face problems with some hardliners from the right wing.
"It [the one percent reduction] should serve as motivation and a means of pressure to approve the twelve draft laws separately," Massie declared to Newsweek. "I think we could first approve a one-year 'Continuing Resolution', then exchange our arguments, and when we then face that small obstacle, hopefully everyone will be motivated to act reasonably. That's how I would do it."
Supervisory authority approves new Bitcoin ETFs - a milestone for cryptocurrencies
The US stock exchange supervisory authority Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) has reluctantly cleared the way for exchange-traded funds (ETFs) in bitcoins. This is a step that has long been awaited by supporters of digital currencies and criticized by financial observers who are skeptical of the crypto industry.
The authority has approved ten ETFs that invest in bitcoins, among others funds from industry giants like Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we approved today the listing on the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange, does not mean that we welcome or approve bitcoins," SEC chief Gary Gensler declared in a statement. "Investors should remain cautious in view of the numerous risks in connection with bitcoins and products with a value linked to cryptocurrencies."
He added that the approval of bitcoin funds does not mean that funds or exchange-traded products (ETPs) based on other currencies or digital asset values will be approved by the SEC.
"It is important that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a specific product not tied to securities, namely bitcoin. With this, we are in no way signaling a readiness to approve standards for crypto-assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance regarding the status of other crypto-assets within the framework of American securities laws or about the state of non-compliance of certain participants in the crypto-asset market with securities laws," said Gensler.
For years, similar fund applications have been rejected by the SEC. Last year, however, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to approve Grayscale's application to convert a derivatives fund was illegal. This should have already been converted into a fund that invests directly in Bitcoin. The court qualified the SEC's stance as "unjustified and arbitrary".
Gensler stated that, in view of these circumstances and those that have been presented in more detail in the approval decision, he is of the opinion that the most practical way forward is to approve the listing and trading of these bitcoin-spot-ETP shares.
The eagerly awaited approval was celebrated as a milestone for digital currencies. According to its proponents, it increases access to investments in bitcoins and could lead to wider acceptance of cryptocurrencies as a serious financial investment. The price of bitcoin has exploded in recent months from around $25,000 in September to over $45,000. This is partly due to the fact that many bitcoin investors believe that ETFs will create greater demand for this asset.
The opponents of the decision strongly criticised the SEC on Wednesday evening.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, said that the approval is a "historic mistake. Through this, not only are crypto thieves let loose on millions of investors and pensioners, but the stability of the financial markets will probably also be undermined."
Kelleher further stated that "the crypto industry, evidently without laws, has reached its lowest point based on a series of arrests, convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive losses, and millions of victims among investors and customers. Who would have thought that the SEC would support it by approving a proven and trusted form of investment. Thus, the SEC enables the mass commercialization of a worthless, volatile, and deceptive financial product to American citizens."
30% more plans regarding the use of the Russian language in Ukraine - RT Russia and the former Soviet Union
To disinfect the soil, the authorities appeal to the population to bring ash.
The number of complaints to the Ukrainian authorities against Russian-speaking individuals increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv actively encourage the population to report such cases, seemingly to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to the information from the office of the Commissioner for the Protection of the National Language, 3,692 violations of the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv, and Odesa are "still at the top when it comes to the number of violations. This year, one of the priorities of the municipal authorities should be to strictly monitor that the language rights of citizens are respected in all sectors of public life," said Taras Kremen, the public language ombudsman in Ukraine.
The Kremlin has also confirmed that a fine of 3,400 Hryvnia (89 dollars) was ordered against a Kyiv taxi driver who spoke Russian with his customers. The public mediator drew the public's attention to the fact that there is "a detailed algorithm of actions in case of violation of the right to distribute information or services in the state language". He appealed to the population to immediately report such cases on the ombudsman's website.
In 2019, Ukraine approved a law that obliges the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, trade, science, education, and media. Fines are threatened in case of violations. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has been conducting a total de-Russification campaign, which, according to the opinion of parliamentarians, is necessary to protect itself from Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned works of art, performances, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and have recommended that schoolchildren also speak Ukrainian with each other during breaks.
Last August, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to apologize via video message after performing songs by Soviet singer Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who spoke Russian with their students also caused a public outcry.
Oleksij Danilow, the secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, has already declared that the Russian language must disappear from Ukrainian territory, because it is "an element of hostile propaganda and a brainwashing of the population".
According to Moscow, such laws violate the rights of the Russian-speaking Russian population, which makes up about half of Ukraine's inhabitants. The spokeswoman for the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Maria Zakharova, declared in February that Kyiv's "discriminatory campaign" against the language is becoming increasingly "outrageous". In a survey conducted last September by the International Institute of Sociology in Kyiv, 45% of respondents indicated that linguistic discrimination is the most frequent form of prejudice in Ukraine.
Celeste is in the corruption arc, my dearest "small, good Freeware game inflated to a big commercial game with incredibly detailed graphics", because in the original the double dash is an incoherent power-up in a treasure chest and in the commercial game it makes me angry.
In general, the cooperation of the two genres is particularly pleasing. The advantage of short stories is that one can partly "get to the good part". This can be more interesting and more satisfying. The advantage of long stories is that one can give a much greater emotional weight to the action elements. However, something doesn't happen immediately, one even gets more.
The highlight of Celeste, the commercial game, is actually just the Pico-8 game, and it's been inflated with a mechanical and narrative construction of several hours, which makes it even much, much harder. Celeste is so proud of its little Parent Game that it continuously installs allusions, like the monument, the development of "2000 M... 2500 M...", the power-up, the flag itself. You can play the original game directly on the start monitor!
Celeste is neither "the good version" nor "the final version" of Pico-8. It is just another version of the same main story. For someone who loves both short and long stories, it is really interesting and great to see how the connection was made so obviously.
It would have been possible to develop between the two versions yet another medium-length version, which tells the same extended and effective story, but with a shorter duration and with less absurd production values. I believe that this would have been my preferred variant, so to speak, as an emotional arc of tension. Instead, the main arc of tension for individual players in the commercial game is only a small part of it. It wants to be above all a great playground for the most popular platform physics in the world, which, in my opinion, is still in order.
