So far I have only needed a general anaesthetic for one operation. This was a "small" neurosurgical intervention to give my brain more space. I was born with a malformation and because of it I developed symptoms after the birth of my children (Chiari malformation). The moment I woke up, I have never forgotten it and I relive it again and again when I watch medical shows, especially those with a neurosurgeon 😂. I have already written down the hospital playlist on a piece of paper and I like it very much at the moment. #kdrama
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before because it was going to snow. When the treatment team took care of me when I woke up from the anaesthesia in the recovery room, my surgeon noticed that I had my eyes open and that the bandage was in front of my eyes. I still miss all that after the operation. But it was still irritating. That was one of the things that gave me the biggest scare I've ever had. I had slept and it was already over.
My period was already over, but I still had to take it off. That's why they gave me that underwear made of mesh fabric, which you wear after giving birth. But in the operating room, you are completely undressed and covered with a sheet. Sometime before I woke up, a friendly nurse changed my underwear. Apart from the births, during which I was awake and received help, or as a baby, no one had ever done anything so private for me. That was also the only time I was in the intensive care unit. Due to the type of operation, I also had to go to the intensive care unit as a precautionary measure.
Because of my operation I had to rest a lot, so I watched seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. The fact that McDreamy was the neurosurgeon helped me. I observed how the patient was positioned to be able to imagine what would happen to me. After my operation in 2018, Hospital Playlist showed more about neurosurgery than any other medical show I watched after Grey's. How beautiful that there is art and entertainment to give meaning to our lives.
Thanks to Hospital Playlist I could transplant a kidney.
Wow!
I often think that millennials were the last generation who could develop relationships with artists without anything being expected of them, or of seeing them critically.
We grew up in a time of media with a collective sense for pop culture, which no longer exists.
We were able to rush into things, without having to ponder where they came from, because at that time it wasn't so easy to find that out.
We didn't have to question the pedestal on which we had already placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
Why do we have such a strong tendency for nostalgia?
When "The Office" was still being shown, my friends and I always ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the series together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes appear at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and marks social media posts with "spoiler warnings" or discusses it in closed groups.
Unconsciously longing for that universal community, which dominated almost everything.
Why do so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or films like "Anchorman", with so many references in one line, that would be memes today.
We have said all the proverbs, assuming that most people understand them.
Even then, one cannot simply assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There is too much, and there is no possibility of systematizing it. Who knows if we will ever get out of this abundance again?
We are caught in a vicious circle of always discovering new content, only to then realize that the artist has a shortage of money or is a miser.
Because we must maintain our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works we liked can also have big flaws.
We engage in parasocial relationships with great caution.
For us it is clear that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on one or the other's toes along the way.
As we have lost the collective consciousness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
Among us there are still those who lift someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when he falls.
We are in a phase of change and I wonder where this will lead.
