It's an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/customize small robot figures, the disadvantage is that you HAVE to build something that is made for war and killing.
As in the noughties. I had Bionicles. These were actually adventurers/heroes with elemental powers, with different personalities and hobbies and so on, but before and after there was only something like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech, with the nonsense of being a weapon that is presented in the accompanying media in an absolutely useless way.
It's clear that those other sources ARE that "the war is bad", but then they still sell killing machines as figures and merchandise. What are we to do?
I think the solution is to separate between homeland and its fictional use, just like one does in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain has DIFFICULTY with that.
Because the figures already look cool and I like how they are built and how their design reflects certain character traits, but then with every set it says: "By the way, this is your laser sword and your (at least one) pistol!"
Probably that has largely to do with the fact that toys for boys almost always have something to do with violence, like for example GI Joe and Transformers, but now honestly, we are in the present.
I'm happy to see Berry's family of pacifist robots printed in 3D ;)
