A self-confessed anarchist, who is keen to keep his identity hidden, nevertheless gives his DNA to a biotechnology company to obtain a dubious overview of his ancestry. What could possibly go wrong?
My wife has chosen that as a starting point. Without going into too much detail here, she believes that a couple of her so-called ancestors are actually not her ancestors. I will support her and observe the effect of genetic drift by means of a small control test. We know quite a lot about our family.
Perhaps there is someone in my family who has been unfaithful, but if one looks at my family roots, for the most part poor, all affairs probably happened in mostly homogeneous communities, markets and ethnic ghettos, lol.
My grandmother left her husband for his brother and I have a great-uncle on the other side of the family, who left his wife for her aunt. My family might be wandering, but it doesn't get very far.
And now my wife has a full moon, because my "extraction" was much faster than expected. I'm sick, maybe his genome shouldn't be begged in such a way.
The results are here and - rataplan, please - they completely match my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, most of which is concentrated in the Scottish Borders, in western Ireland, Wales and Cornwall. The Breton part is not large, perhaps because it is so close to Cornwall that there is no difference for me, or that my Breton family part does not come from there.
