The development of humanity continues without end. Even in difficult times, we develop and adapt. In the markets, there is still great prosperity, and technological progress is advancing. With the recent discovery of Ignniat, humanity has catapulted itself to supreme heights, but the greatest is yet to come. This newly acquired knowledge, which humanity receives here, can only be valued as divine intervention, and the Gods will rejoice at our presence in heaven. The company Karascene has had Ignniat intensively examined and assesses the potential of this mineral as very great. And no worries: according to the examinations, there are no side effects or problems with the exploitation of Ignniat. This mineral is definitely for something bigger.
January 14, 2543, 22:26.
In a click. The same stream repeated itself in a loop: the day when the world was not devastated. My father had to put it down every time he saw that I couldn't take my eyes off it. My stomach turned seeing his depressed expression. I always feel bad when that stream plays, because it still awakens so many memories, but none of them very good. I'm trying to distract myself with other thoughts. I constantly try to entertain him and chase away his bad mood, by making him at least a little happy, but today I'm tired.
I close the door more carefully and call to my father: "I'm going out for a bit, dinner is in the fridge." No answer. What else. Mostly he doesn't hear me, he'll probably get cold alone. I close the door and sigh again, after it has closed completely. I almost forgot to put my hands on the cold metal scanner to close the door. If there was something that characterized that apartment, it was its equipment with modern technology, which, however, corresponded to most buildings. For a long time, no other technology was used anymore.
During that cold and rainy night, I took my exploratory walk late through Paltricus - a privilege reserved for those who had escaped the mutation by fleeing or by sheer luck. The night was illuminated by bright stars that were already thousands of years old. It must be lonely in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful market, but one felt more like in a birdcage than in a luxurious home. The market was overloaded with apartments, houses, and other residential buildings, mostly with several hundred floors, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a boon for technology and architecture and had expanded our living base. However, the public knows very little about the mineral, especially because it is kept strictly secret.
To free myself from my troubled thoughts, I set off to drink a coffee in my favorite local. Because of the rumor that a leper had been going around in the region, he is avoided by most people. That's what those who have been infected with the virus are called. But that has never worried me - I have already cleaned up a lot of dirt in my life - and the owner is a great guy. Who would give up a free coffee in exchange for a nocturnal conversation?
When I entered, my discomfort was not caused by a strong staircase, and the smell of freshly brewed coffee reached my nose. Anton, the owner of the place, stood as always behind the counter. The place was practically empty, with the exception of a few people in the back. After the long walk, I approached the bar exhausted, let myself fall onto one of the stools, and sighed. I saw Anton, and he brought me the usual. "Hello Lilith, a long night?", his hoarse voice echoed through the folds of my brain. "Something like that," I replied faintly and became more tired with each passing second.
To shake off my tiredness, I took a few sips from the coffee in front of me. "Are things still going badly after the story with the leper...?" I spoke softly, so as not to scare away the last guests from Anton's place. He nodded, while he cleaned a glass with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I never came here to drink a cocktail. Behind me I could hear murmuring, but the conversation between Anton and me was rather short this evening. With a short farewell sign and a little more energy than before, I left the place.
It was often not the best idea to walk through the dark streets late at night. But still better than staying in that stuffy apartment and listening to the neighbors having sex. You heard them more often than your own music. With a short sigh, I turned my gaze back to the road ahead of me. I'll probably go to AI's shop, the pawnbroker, to pass the time looking at the interesting old stuff there. When I heard footsteps right behind me, I was confirmed in my decision. Maybe I worry too much, but in this neighborhood, you were only safe if you didn't let yourself be robbed or beaten up. The neighborhood was known for the mafia and gang crime...
Self-satisfied. Only half of humanity remains and it still doesn't give up. I was also faster, the pawn shop was just around the corner and it was also getting dark. When I stood in front of an illuminated sign with the inscription "Alborn's Pawn Shop", a quick glance over my shoulder confirmed to me that I was no longer being pursued. With a calmer step, I entered the shop. This place was rather off the radar, as Alborn often took in mutants who were in Paltricus without permission. It was dark in the shop and AI was curiously not there either. No fugitives. Nothing. Something was curious here.
Carefully I slipped into the back part of the shop, where one could hear a murmur and low voices behind a metal grate that could be removed with a few hand movements. I slipped into the ventilation shaft - at the moment the simplest and safest method. When I pushed myself through, I heard conversations between strangely dressed men. Then I saw AI in chains. It was already clear that they would eventually catch him.
She really liked Alborn, but that was too big a number for me. I really shouldn't stick my nose into other people's business, especially not if they are looking for a dispute with the concentrated state authorities. Nevertheless, I couldn't do otherwise. Sighing softly, I pulled the cat out from under me from its fixation and let myself down into the quiet room. "Psst. AI. AI!" I hissed and when he didn't answer, I raised my voice. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise I'll catch you."
"But you...", I said quietly to myself. While we tried to loosen the chains around his arm, we heard voices approaching and the silent footsteps grew louder and louder. "Quick! Get back into the chimney and disappear. Don't come back under any circumstances. If we see each other again, then not in this market." He spoke quickly and the panic in his eyes didn't exactly help me calm down. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay any longer. Cac, AI. After I had left the ventilation shaft, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Should I take him to the other... market? So many thoughts swirling through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I was intensely occupied with external markets and the capital of the infected. She was named Alcatraz, after the prison of the same name. The name fit very well with what I had read. Not to mention that the non-mutants had immediately cut all land connections to the infected areas. A tragedy.
A deafening silence surrounded me on the way home. Thoughts raced through my head and I almost burst because I couldn't help AI. When I finally got home after that terrible walk, I was close to tears and the thunderclaps coming from the clouds above me could put anyone in fear and terror. My father was already asleep on the sofa. It was a rerun of a movie from about 10-12 years ago. Sighing, I quietly slipped into my room. I let myself fall onto my bed. I could barely keep my eyes open and fell asleep immediately.
EXPLOSION
January 19, 2543, 2:34 PM.
Time passed quickly. A few days ago Alborn was not transported away. We didn't know. Only that they had taken him somewhere. The men's clothing seemed unfamiliar to me, but I simply couldn't remember where from. Sighing, I placed my hands on the system in front of me that glowed red and purple - as if it would have been easy for me. I doubt they had additionally locked it... But I'll stop talking about it. But of course I quickly dismissed my moral reservations. My finger moved telekinetically over the keyboard and called up different monitors. I am quite good. I was quite well-known on several websites, they called me "SPIERT" there. A very striking name. I admit that I use the name SPI3RT on every website, but I like the thought that I got it from others.
I load the images from the surveillance cameras onto my mobile device and examine each one exactly. Nothing. As if they had never been there. That makes no sense. The cameras are well secured, even against remote access. How...? SHIT. I'm going to wash my face to get the thoughts out of my head. I'm at the door, I've put on my shoes and grabbed my keys. "I'll be right back, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answered anyway. He was probably busy with something more important than me again.
When I left my apartment, I stumbled briefly and a shiver ran down my spine. Disturbing. I ignored the feeling and forced myself to go to the pawn shop to do some research. But my legs carried me to Anton's small bar. It was very quiet there and I desperately needed someone to talk to. Who would be better suited than a bartender who owed me money?
It was extraordinarily full, full of people I had never seen before. Actually, Anton always worked alone and he was really stressed by the many guests. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low voice to annoy him a little. He flinched briefly and I had to laugh softly when I saw the relief on his face. "Oh, Lilith, don't give me such a fright...", he said softly with a tired voice. "It looks like you have a lot to do... Can I help? There's a lot going on here." I certainly had no desire to serve those idiots, but I felt sorry for Anton because he had to deal with it all alone. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later...", he stammered and looked at me with his dog's eyes. Advanced warfare tactics...
Since I had already exchanged my clothes for a short work uniform, I helped Anton get out of the bar. With the constant attempts to flirt and attract my attention, which, to be honest, didn't really bother me, the work went quickly. After the service, I'll talk to Anton. I have to forget AI, even though I know that I will do further research in his pawn shop after the service in the bar, but still...
Flames shot out of Thassalin's throat, as the gigantic Thraki had already set a piece of the destined forest on fire and circled above to identify movements. Curiously, the unsettling crackling behind him stopped when he became quieter. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What does that mean, Tenuk, you've already transformed into a Thracian!"
"When I was half-asleep, that's totally different from being suddenly snatched up by a gigantic pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it Kayel?"
Kayel apparently wasn't of Nyssi's opinion. He looked less black than usual and his claws had dug so deep into Thassalin's back that Traki lost blood. Thassalin acted as if nothing had happened. Nevertheless, he realized that he had embarrassed his new friends, and he sat down in a corner.
"I'm sick, but I'll manage somehow. Because I have to take care of that!"
"But did you also have to drag us along with you?", Tenuk grumbled, when he slid down Thassalin's back and snuggled up to his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! Our big and strong fighter we left in the stable! How can he ever catch up with us again?"
"He's not bad at having a good idea...", Nyssi mumbled. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not stupid."
"Well, but I'm Reto, can I speak?"
He nodded and turned to Tenuk. "Of course he can talk."
"Have you ever seen Reto drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him drive a small car like Kayel's either. Besides, he's only just started taking the car to work, because you always drive us. He only has his bike."
They were interrupted by laughter. Thassalin always seemed to find something extremely funny, but no one knew why he was laughing. It took a while until Thassalin calmed down.
"I'm sick, but I imagine your gigantic love in a small child's bicycle. That was hilarious! I wish I had a way of telepathy. A wonderful imagination! One that I can't share!"
Kayel sighed, because he could imagine Thassalin's thoughts. "Yes, that's true. But what did you dream and why did you fly away so unexpectedly?"
The goblin grumbled, turned away and disappeared. When he returned a short time later, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, snow-white dragon creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I SMELL THEIR SCENT. I KNOW THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING TORMENTS ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY DANGEROUS."
The mighty Thraki was not alone tonight. Nysski and Kayel were also not alone and had looked attentively towards a gap in the anchor. Something big and black stared at them and snorted. Whatever it was, it opened two pairs of gigantic wings and flew towards Thassalin without bothering about the three smaller creatures between them. Kayel and Tenuk had just been able to get to safety, but Nyssi was pulled along and almost crashed into Thassalin.
He reacted quickly to that attack by grabbing Nyssi and patting her on the back with his incredibly long and agile tail, before he himself spun into the air. The black creature with double wings pursued them with great speed.
Kayel had reloaded, while he took his rifle off his back and opened a bag with a belt of ammunition inside. He hung the belt around his chest, but quickly realised that Nyssi, the Thraki and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?", Kayel asked.
"Are you going to persecute him?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... one of them is a gigantic monster!"
"And then? I'm here with a loaded gun in my hand and could start shooting immediately. Well, as they say - I should see that, to be able to touch it."
Tenuk had to turn around, so he went back to have more space. With a light and painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his skin transformed into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly changed into a normal Thracian warrior, but his eyes remained red.
"Look at that."
As in Thrace, Tenuk, with an ordinary appearance, now had a splendid scale shield along his back. And from his back had also grown two spines, so that Kayel could hold on to them, which was practical. It took a few days until Tenuk managed to leave, but once in the air, he was able to orient himself quickly and tried to take up the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realised that they were not alone. A second strange creature shot past them and Tenuk was barely able to avoid a collision.
"Is that really the other gigantic monster, the one Lanex is already afraid of?" Kayel rubbed his forehead. He tried to shoot at the second beast, but missed and quickly reloaded.
He didn't answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight towards Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was chasing them. Kayel turned awkwardly to get the monster in sight. The fact that it was chasing them was an advantage for Kayel, so he could aim and shoot better. Two shots hit the beast's upper wings. It screamed in pain and lowered itself under the trees. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still chasing them, but it certainly couldn't keep up with them.
A good while ago Nyssi was desperately holding on, while Thassalin was giving and spitting flames at the soot monster. The creature was definitely wounded. It seemed to be very enraged, but not ready to give up. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin stopped, Nyssi took the opportunity to pick up his own weapon, an old and good slingshot. Even if he didn't have it for such purposes, maybe the cruel things would at least scare the black beast?
No, it doesn't seem so. The creature only flapped and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin was agile enough, despite her size, and dodged, but Nyssi gave a cry when she almost lost her last hold on Thassalin's not-so-smooth scales.
"HOW DO WE KILL HER?", Nyssi hurried.
"BETTER THEIR HEADS!"
"THAT'S GETTING DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin whistled and then pulled himself up onto a ridge, closer to the mountain he called his home. The wild beast followed, but was slightly overcome by panic when a ray of fire touched it from behind. It hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. It was even more overcome by panic when Thassalin came closer and whipped his tail against its head and knocked it off its path.
Muttering and hissing, she flew up and spat into the air. Suddenly everything became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky, replacing it with a level of eternal night.
When Thassalin saw nothing more, he tried to retreat. He noticed how he had scraped himself on the branches before finally falling into a ravine. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and swooped directly down towards him, dragging the black mist with it.
"Kayel!", Tenuk called, when he had pulled himself out of the snow and started to throw stones, to scare Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness. "What shall we do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Giudem and Nyssi got up with difficulty. He was sure he had broken something, but his special and supernatural powers were already beginning to work. For Thassalin, unfortunately, that was not the case. He was lying close to the only plant that had not been crushed under his weight. Nyssi tried hard to get closer to Thassalin, but he could barely see two meters. Everything was dark and wrapped in huge shadows. And in that shadow there was someone who was screaming and groaning.
A tail, armed and anxious, thrashed down to the ground next to Nyssi and beat around him. He noticed, however, that the tail was only furiously lashing around itself without intending to touch him. The beast, or what little Nyssi saw or felt of it, grinned and tried to grasp with its claws the shadows it created itself. Something shot through the darkness, burrowed into the monster and made it completely confused.
Totally stunned, he shot the monster in the chest and it didn't move, it fell to the ground and lay there, motionless. The darkness around them cleared and they saw what had happened: Kayel was standing on the beast and holding his rifle, smoking.
"That was good... the most spectacular shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel whispered. His eyes were black and sparkling, and a dark energy enveloped his body. But as he grumbled, the warmth returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their usual yellow color.
It was a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed those particular dark forces. He rarely used them, because they disturbed and frightened many. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use those forces even in any kind of darkness. And as Kayel behaved, he also seemed to be quite surprised.
"Is everything in order with you?", Nyssi asked about that.
"Yes, I want to bathe. I'll go to the stream, I'll be back soon in a hurry with me." Kayel contemplated his work, while Tenuk flew closer, hid beside him and changed back into his normal form of Spast.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its fur was black like a raven and shaggy, but the slime stuck firmly to its body. It had four wings and four limbs that all ended in long, sharp claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what kind of monster they had in front of them, they heard something crackle that had jumped out of a nearby bush. But it didn't reach them, because a familiar vehicle jumped in from the side, so the monster went pale and stopped at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to risk anything. He grabbed his rifle, shot without hesitation at its head, and the creature was dead on the spot.
"Oops...", Retvik stammered from the driver's seat, before he reluctantly turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Um, that's actually not allowed here. Is everything alright with you all?"
"You missed the whole action," Tenuk murmured. "Where were you?"
"You simply left me behind. I arrived as quickly as possible...", Retvik sighed. "May I ask what horrible beasts these are?"
Thassalin, who was back on his feet, answered Retvik's question with a good-natured smile. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a little dazed, but not seriously injured.
"I'll kill the corrupt! The infected monsters. Creatures that had come from here, when corruption attacked your gods."
"You mean the horrible monster-like creature that we have... helped to kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"Yes. Exactly that. Maybe even more. But I didn't know how to shoot him in the head. I have no firearm. And two against one is unfair, isn't it?"  Thassalin limped to Kayel and patted him on the head. "Thank you very much, little one. You remind me of my old friend Arkadin. Just not so terrible and not so capable of destroying an entire universe."
"Ehm... thanks... I think..." Kayel shrugged. "So, are we finally here?"
Nyssi had finished the hunt. He had grabbed his camera and taken a few pictures of the animals that were now definitely dead. Then he took out his favorite weapon, the dagger adorned with the god of the dead, and began to saw off one of the animal's horns. Afterwards, he started with the second. Just as Nyssi had finished, the animals suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes within seconds. The same happened with the horns that Nyssi had already cut off.
"Well, that's practical and not practical at the same time...", Nyssi said. "But at least I'll have the photos, I hope."
